    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Real Nuisance</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gretchen Adamek letter on March 30 article about hypochondria holds that those patients who imagine illness do experience many physical symptoms of illness (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A New Era in Treating Imaginary Ills'' (March 30): Anyone who has had a close relative who suffers from hypochondria knows how frustrating and exhausting dealing with him or her can be.</p>
        <p>As the article points out, the symptoms that a hypochondriac experiences are real. The heart does race, the vision blurs, the chest constricts. Whatever the pathology, to call these ills imaginary is pejorative.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A New Era in Treating Imaginary Ills'' (March 30): Anyone who has had a close relative who suffers from hypochondria knows how frustrating and exhausting dealing with him or her can be.</p>
        <p>As the article points out, the symptoms that a hypochondriac experiences are real. The heart does race, the vision blurs, the chest constricts. Whatever the pathology, to call these ills imaginary is pejorative.</p>
        <p>After all, you wouldn't refer to the voices heard by some schizophrenics as their imaginary friends, would you?</p>
        <p>GRETCHEN ADAMEK  East Hartford, Conn.</p>
      </block>
